land","Newbie, Newbeggin, Angus, Scotland":"Angus, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1470–before 20 December 1536":"1470–before 20 December 1536","1470–1536":"1470–1536","1472–1536":"1472–1536","1489–1547":"1489–1547","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1425–1504":"1425–1504","1450–1478":"1450–1478","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","Abt 1500":"about 1500","1470":"1470","1547":"1547","1536":"1536","1425":"1425","1478":"1478","1489":"1489","1500":"1500","about 1499":"about 1499","1504":"1504","before 20 December 1536":"before 20 December 1536","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Newbie, Newbeggin, Angus, Scotland":"Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Clare): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corra</b> or <b>Ó Corraidh</b>, see   Corr  . Alternatively, a shortened and altered form of   McCorry  .","Scottish: variant of   Corrie  .","Americanized form of Arabic   Khoury   or   Khouri   ‘priest’. Compare   Cory  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Corr","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Aidan, Brendan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Corra</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corra</i>’, a personal name from <i>corr</i> ‘spear, pointed object’. It is occasionally translated into English as   Weir   (from Irish <i>cora</i> ‘weir’)."]}]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Herbert Corry of Kelwood and Newbie was born in 1470, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Thomas Corry, was 45 and his mother, Eufemia de Herries Lindsay, was 20. He married Esota Murray about 1499, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 20 December 1536, in Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1470–before 20 December 1536":"1470–enne 20. detsembrit 1536","1470–1536":"1470–1536","1472–1536":"1472–1536","1489–1547":"1489–1547","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1425–1504":"1425–1504","1450–1478":"1450–1478","145